          "title": "The roaring lion and the fourfold restoration (5:8-11)",
          "body": "The chapter pivots abruptly at 5:8 — no connective, two staccato imperatives: *be sober, be on the alert*. The unseen enemy is named in dual register: *antidikos* (legal adversary, courtroom prosecutor) and *diabolos* (slanderer). He is pictured as *a roaring lion* (*leōn ōruomenos*) *prowling* and *seeking someone to devour*. The image draws from Psalm 22:13 — the same psalm Christ prayed from the cross. The believer's response is not flight but firm stand: *resist* (*antistēte*) *him, firm in your faith*. Resistance is corporate — *knowing that the same experiences of suffering are being accomplished by your brethren* throughout the world. Then 5:10 lands the chapter's brightest promise: after a *little while* of suffering, *the God of all grace... will Himself* (*autos*) *perfect, confirm, strengthen, and establish you*. Four verbs, intensifying: mend (*katartisei*), make firm (*stērixei*), strengthen (*sthenōsei*), ground on a foundation (*themeliōsei*). The work is God's own — *autos*. The doxology of 5:11 seals it: *to Him be dominion forever*."
